<p>Hi friends and family, it's true, I'm leaving Apple.</p>
<p>On hearing this news, people tend to want an explanation, and so here I hope to answer your questions. I made some sections clickable for more detail, because this is the type of skill I have now, and I'm using it to express myself here.</p>

{{#collapse-question header="Was it Apple's fault? (no)"}}
  <p>Apple's been awesome. I've learned a ton, made some great fiends, saved most of what I earned, eaten the best food of my life, and got to help out in making what still believe are some of the highest-quality computers in the world, and now I know first hand the kind of care that goes into them.</p>
  <p>There were always tradeoffs for me. The long commute (which I voluntarily endured to save money) was a big drag, and it's a side effect of the bay area being in a bit of a insane mess of economic boom right now. Even as a programmer that could supposedly be gentrifying; moving to the south bay was both more expensive than I wanted to pay, and not an area I had much interest in other than work convenience.</p>
  <p>Finally, the one thing they could never offer me is freedom to work on what I wanted to. Ultimately I'm a very self-driven person as long as I have the freedom to set my own priorities and pursue them as I like, and I have a long list of things I'd like to do, but that's something I'll probably never get in a big corporation, hence needing to spend at least some time out of one.</p>
{{/collapse-question}}

<p>I have another project I'm excited to start on.</p>

